GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 2
HOUSE BILL 934
Committee Substitute Favorable 5/6/25
Short Title: AI Regulatory Reform Act. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
April 14, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT AMENDING THE CRIMINAL LAWS TO CREATE THE OFFENSE OF
3 UNLAWFUL DISTRIBUTION OF A DEEPFAKE AND AMENDING THE CIVIL
4 PROCEDURE LAWS TO GRANT IMMUNITY FROM CIVIL LIABILITY TO
5 DEVELOPERS OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE PRODUCTS USED BY LEARNED
6 PROFESSIONALS.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8 SECTION 1.(a) Article 60 of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes is amended by
9 adding a new section to read:
10 "§ 14-459. Unlawful distribution of a deepfake.
11 (a) Definitions. – For purposes of this section, the following definitions apply:
12 (1) Deepfake. – An image, audio recording, or video recording that is created with
13 the intent to deceive and is digitally altered or generated to inauthentically
14 depict a natural person speaking or acting in a manner that the person did not
15 actually speak or act, in such a manner that a reasonable person would not
16 know that the depiction is false. A work of artistic or newsworthy value,
17 including commentary, criticism, satire, or parody, is not a deepfake.
18 (2) Interactive computer service. – Any information service, system, or access
19 software provider that provides or enables computer access by multiple users
20 to a computer server, including specifically a service or system that provides
21 access to the internet and such systems operated or services offered by
22 libraries or educational institutions.
23 (b) Offense. – It is unlawful for a person, without the affirmative consent of the depicted
24 individual, to knowingly do any of the following for the purpose of (i) harassing, extorting,
25 threatening, or causing physical, emotional, reputational, or economic harm to an individual
26 falsely depicted or (ii) injuring a candidate for elected office or influencing an election:
27 (1) Create a deepfake with an intent to distribute the deepfake.
28 (2) Distribute a deepfake.
29 (3) Solicit the creation of a deepfake with an intent to distribute the deepfake.
30 (c) Punishment. – A violation of this section is punishable as a Class 1 misdemeanor.
31 (d) Civil Action. – In addition to any other remedies at law or in equity, including an
32 order by the court to destroy any deepfake disclosed in violation of this section, any person
33 aggrieved by a violation of subsection (b) of this section has a civil cause of action against any
34 person who creates or distributes the deepfake in violation of subsection (b) of this section and
35 is entitled to recover from the other person any of the following:
*H934-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Actual damages, but not less than liquidated damages, to be computed at the
2 rate of one thousand dollars ($1,000) for each time the deepfake is
3 redistributed or in the amount of ten thousand dollars ($10,000), whichever is
4 higher.
5 (2) Punitive damages.
6 (3) A reasonable attorneys' fee and other litigation costs reasonably incurred.
7 (e) Exceptions. – The following entities shall not be liable for the actions of a person that
8 uses that entity's service or technology in the commission of an offense under subsection (b) of
9 this section:
10 (1) An interactive computer service.
11 (2) A provider or developer of any technology used in the creation of a deepfake.
12 (f) Other Sanctions or Remedies Not Precluded. – A violation of this section is an offense
13 additional to other civil and criminal provisions and is not intended to repeal or preclude any
14 other sanctions or remedies."
15 SECTION 1.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
16 offenses committed on or after that date.
17 SECTION 2.(a) Chapter 1 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
18 Article to read:
19 "Article 43G.
20 "Actions Pertaining to Artificial Intelligence.
21 "§ 1-539.30. Definitions.
22 The following definitions apply in this Article:
23 (1) Artificial intelligence product or AI product. – Any algorithm, product,
24 software, or system that:
25 a. Performs tasks that would typically require human intelligence, such
26 as reasoning, language processing, or decision making;
27 b. Is designed to operate with some degree of autonomy;
28 c. Uses techniques that enable the system to improve its performance
29 over time or through exposure to data; and
30 d. Is marketed, distributed, licensed, or otherwise made available for use,
31 whether as a stand-alone product or as a component integrated into
32 other products or services.
33 (2) Client. – Any person who engages the services of a learned professional and
34 who relies upon the learned professional's expertise, judgment, and advice
35 where the professional relationship with the learned professional is governed
36 by professional standards, codes of conduct, or regulations.
37 (3) Developer. – Any person that meets any of the following:
38 a. Creates, designs, programs, trains, modifies, or substantially
39 contributes to the creation or modification of an AI product.
40 b. Exercises control over the AI product's design specifications,
41 functionality, capabilities, limitations, or intended uses.
42 c. Tests, validates, documents, or certifies an AI product prior to its
43 release or deployment.
44 d. Markets, distributes, licenses, or makes available an AI product under
45 their own name, brand, or trademark, regardless of whether they
46 created the original underlying technology.
47 e. Either creates an original AI product or is a secondary developer who
48 substantially modifies, retrains, or adapts an existing AI product for a
49 new use or market.
50 (4) Error. – Any output, action, recommendation, or omission by an AI product
51 that produces objectively incorrect information. The term includes when an
Page 2 House Bill 934-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 AI product fails to perform a function or task that it expressly or implicitly
2 represents itself as capable of performing.
3 (5) Interactive computer service. – Any information service, system, or access
4 software provider that provides or enables computer access by multiple users
5 to a computer server, including specifically a service or system that provides
6 access to the internet and such systems operated or services offered by
7 libraries or educational institutions.
8 (6) Learned professional. – Any individual who meets all of the following:
9 a. Possesses specialized education, training, knowledge, or skill in a
10 recognized profession.
11 b. Is licensed, certified, or otherwise authorized by an occupational
12 licensing board to practice in their field in this State.
13 c. Is bound by professional standards, ethical obligations, and a duty of
14 care to clients.
15 d. Exercises independent professional judgment when utilizing tools,
16 including AI products, in the course of rendering professional services.
17 e. Is expected to possess sufficient knowledge to evaluate the
18 appropriateness, limitations, and risks of tools employed in their
19 professional practice, including artificial intelligence products, as they
20 pertain to a specific client matter.
21 "§ 1-539.31. Immunity from civil liability for artificial intelligence developers.
22 When a learned professional uses an artificial intelligence program or product in the course
23 of providing professional services to a client, the learned professional is solely responsible for
24 any damage to the client resulting from errors generated by the artificial intelligence product.
25 The following entities shall not be liable for the actions of the learned professional in use of the
26 artificial intelligence product:
27 (1) The developer of the artificial intelligence product.
28 (2) An interactive computer service.
29 "§ 1-539.32. Other privileges and immunities.
30 This Article does not affect any other immunities from civil liability established by the
31 General Statutes or available at common law."
32 SECTION 2.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
33 acts or omissions occurring on or after that date.
34 SECTION 3. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
35 law.
